  "prompt": "Is using \"hairs\" instead of \"hair\" grammatically incorrect?",
  "response": "In general, when referring to the hair on someone's head, the uncountable form \"hair\" is used. For example, \"She has beautiful hair.\" Using \"hairs\" in this context would be incorrect.\n\nHowever, \"hairs\" can be used in certain situations:\n\n1. **Countable hairs**: When referring to individual strands of hair, \"hairs\" is correct. For example, \"I found a few grey hairs.\"\n\n2. **Specific parts of the body**: When talking about hair on specific parts of the body other than the head, \"hairs\" can be used. For example, \"The hairs on his arm stood up.\"\n\n3. **In idiomatic expressions**: Some idiomatic expressions use \"hairs.\" For example, \"splitting hairs\" means to argue about tiny, unimportant details.\n\nIn summary, using \"hairs\" instead of \"hair\" is not always incorrect; it depends on the context.",
